<node CREATED="1295834016611" ID="ID_130609155" MODIFIED="1295834020428" TEXT="Bitwise Operations">
<node CREATED="1295834582611" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1467088234" MODIFIED="1295834659266" TEXT="Python supports most of the numeric expressions available in the C language. This includes operators that treat integers as &apos;&apos;strings of binary bits&apos;&apos;. (&#x9019;&#x88e1;&#x7684; &quot;string&quot; &#x8ddf;&#x5b57;&#x4e32;&#x6c92;&#x6709;&#x95dc;&#x4fc2;&#xff0c;&#x800c;&#x662f; &#x201c;&#x4e00;&#x9023;&#x4e32;&#x7684;...&#x201d;)">
<node CREATED="1295834926471" ID="ID_1459624947" MODIFIED="1295835027947" TEXT="&gt;&gt;&gt; x = 1 # 0001&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; x &lt;&lt; 2 # Shift left 2 bits: 0100&#xa;4&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; x | 2 # Bitwise OR: 0011 (x &#x9084;&#x662f; 0001)&#xa;3&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; x &amp; 1 # Bitwise AND: 0001&#xa;1&#xa;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1295834807868" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_804228960" MODIFIED="1295834809683" TEXT="Such bit-masking operations allow us to encode multiple flags and other values within a single integer.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1295835392383" ID="ID_1575682686" MODIFIED="1295835399558" TEXT="It&#x2019;s supported if you need it, and it comes in handy if your Python code must deal with things like network packets or packed binary data produced by a C program."/>
<node CREATED="1295835399843" ID="ID_652568759" MODIFIED="1295835412484" TEXT="Be aware, though, that bitwise operations are often not as important in a high-level language such as Python as they are in a low-level language such as C."/>
<node CREATED="1295835413024" ID="ID_1328466139" MODIFIED="1295835458567" TEXT="As a rule of thumb, if you find yourself wanting to flip bits in Python, you should think about which language you&#x2019;re really coding. In general, there are often better ways to encode information in Python than bit strings.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<icon BUILTIN="messagebox_warning"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1295838485904" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_836110221" MODIFIED="1295838492841" TEXT="Example">
<node CREATED="1295838494144" ID="ID_1852183836" MODIFIED="1295838495605" TEXT="&gt;&gt;&gt; FLAG_1 = 0b0001&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; FLAG_2 = 0b0010&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; FLAG_3 = 0b0100&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; flag = FLAG_1 | FLAG_3&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; flag &amp; FLAG_1 == FLAG_1&#xa;True&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; flag &amp; FLAG_2 == FLAG_2&#xa;False&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; flag &amp; FLAG_3 == FLAG_3&#xa;True&#xa;"/>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1295835199324" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_793206126" MODIFIED="1295835199324" TEXT="This is one area where the binary and hexadecimal number support in Python 2.6 and 3.0 become especially useful&#x2014;they allow us to code and inspect numbers by &apos;&apos;bit-strings&apos;&apos;:">
<node CREATED="1295835235597" ID="ID_382617182" MODIFIED="1295835237239" TEXT="&gt;&gt;&gt; X = 0b0001 # Binary literals&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; X &lt;&lt; 2 # Shift left&#xa;4&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; bin(X &lt;&lt; 2) # Binary digits string&#xa;&apos;0b100&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; bin(X | 0b010) # Bitwise OR&#xa;&apos;0b11&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; bin(X &amp; 0b1) # Bitwise AND&#xa;&apos;0b1&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; X = 0xFF # Hex literals&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; bin(X)&#xa;&apos;0b11111111&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; X ^ 0b10101010 # Bitwise XOR&#xa;85&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; bin(X ^ 0b10101010)&#xa;&apos;0b1010101&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; int(&apos;1010101&apos;, 2) # String to int per base&#xa;85&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; hex(85) # Hex digit string&#xa;&apos;0x55&apos;&#xa;"/>
</node>
