</node>
<node CREATED="1287472377254" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_76592112" MODIFIED="1287472377628" TEXT="__init__.py">
<node CREATED="1287480197921" ID="ID_1963229779" MODIFIED="1287480207499" TEXT="If you choose to use package imports, there is one more constraint you must follow: each directory named within the path of a package import statement must contain a file named `__init__.py`, or your package imports will fail."/>
<node CREATED="1287480208005" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_72119083" MODIFIED="1291489984006" TEXT="That is, in the example we&#x2019;ve been using, both `dir1` and `dir2` must contain a file called `__init__.py`">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1291489986500" ID="ID_612736232" MODIFIED="1291489997348" TEXT="The container directory `dir0` does not require such a file because it&#x2019;s not listed in the `import` statement itself (this file will simply be ignored if present.).">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<icon BUILTIN="messagebox_warning"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287480319381" ID="ID_760518198" MODIFIED="1287543369330" TEXT="dir0\ # Container on module search path&#xa;  dir1\&#xa;    __init__.py&#xa;    dir2\&#xa;      __init__.py&#xa;      mod.py&#xa;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287480567027" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_183412213" MODIFIED="1291490037413" TEXT="The `__init__.py` files can contain Python code, just like normal module files. They are partly present as a &apos;&apos;declaration&apos;&apos; to Python, however, and can be &apos;&apos;completely empty&apos;&apos;.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1287480576574" ID="ID_1517566803" MODIFIED="1287480747203" TEXT="As declarations, these files serve to prevent directories with common names from unintentionally hiding true modules that appear later on the module search path. Without this safeguard, Python might pick a directory that has nothing to do with your code, just because it appears in an earlier directory on the search path. (&#x660e;&#x78ba;&#x5ba3;&#x544a;&#x67d0;&#x500b;&#x8cc7;&#x6599;&#x593e;&#x662f;&#x500b; package &#x800c;&#x8a00;, &#x907f;&#x514d; module search path &#x88e1;&#x6709;&#x500b;&#x540c;&#x540d;&#x4f46;&#x4ec0;&#x9ebc;&#x6771;&#x897f;&#x90fd;&#x6c92;&#x6709;&#x7684;&#x8cc7;&#x6599;&#x593e;&#x652a;&#x5c40;)"/>
<node CREATED="1287481445714" ID="ID_1474268204" MODIFIED="1287481445714" TEXT="You can also simply leave these files empty, if their roles are beyond your needs (and frankly, they are often empty in practice). They must exist, though, for your directory imports to work at all."/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287480657812" ID="ID_689481278" MODIFIED="1287480660853" TEXT="More generally, the `__init__.py` file serves as a &apos;&apos;hook&apos;&apos; for &apos;&apos;package-initialization-time actions&apos;&apos;, generates a module namespace for a directory, and implements the behavior of `from *` (i.e., `from .. import *`) statements when used with directory imports.">
<node CREATED="1287480767062" ID="ID_46685334" MODIFIED="1287480767062" TEXT="Package initialization">
<node CREATED="1287480818594" ID="ID_1417829826" MODIFIED="1287480818594" TEXT="The first time Python imports through a directory, it automatically runs all the code in the directory&#x2019;s `__init__.py` file. Because of that, these files are a natural place to put code to initialize the state required by files in a package."/>
<node CREATED="1287480823777" ID="ID_1762111953" MODIFIED="1287480823777" TEXT="Typically, `__init__.py` files are not meant to be useful if executed directly; they are run automatically when a package is first accessed."/>
<node CREATED="1287504357236" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_205814589" MODIFIED="1287504855916" TEXT="`import` statements run each directory&#x2019;s initialization file the first time that directory is traversed, as Python &apos;&apos;descends the path&apos;&apos;">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1287504312724" ID="ID_1162928917" MODIFIED="1287504316392" TEXT="# dir1\__init__.py&#xa;print(&apos;dir1 init&apos;)&#xa;x = 1&#xa;&#xa;# dir1\dir2\__init__.py&#xa;print(&apos;dir2 init&apos;)&#xa;y = 2&#xa;&#xa;# dir1\dir2\mod.py&#xa;print(&apos;in mod.py&apos;)&#xa;z = 3&#xa;"/>
<node CREATED="1287504856714" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_658240584" MODIFIED="1287504871734" TEXT="`print` statements are included here to trace their execution. As with module files, an already imported directory may be passed to `reload` to force reexecution of that single item.">
<node CREATED="1287504464462" ID="ID_156761404" MODIFIED="1287504466230" TEXT="% python&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1.dir2.mod # First imports run init files&#xa;dir1 init&#xa;dir2 init&#xa;in mod.py&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1.dir2.mod # Later imports do not&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; from imp import reload # Needed in 3.0&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; reload(dir1)&#xa;dir1 init&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1&apos; from &apos;dir1\__init__.pyc&apos;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; reload(dir1.dir2)&#xa;dir2 init&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1.dir2&apos; from &apos;dir1\dir2\__init__.pyc&apos;&gt;&#xa;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287504482769" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_850636122" MODIFIED="1287504518406" TEXT="Once imported, the path in your `import` statement becomes a &apos;&apos;nested object path&apos;&apos; in your script. Here, `mod` is an object nested in the object `dir2`, which in turn is nested in the object `dir1`:">
<node CREATED="1287504030316" ID="ID_549106230" MODIFIED="1287504031873" TEXT="&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1&apos; from &apos;dir1\__init__.pyc&apos;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1.dir2&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1.dir2&apos; from &apos;dir1\dir2\__init__.pyc&apos;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1.dir2.mod&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1.dir2.mod&apos; from &apos;dir1\dir2\mod.pyc&apos;&gt;&#xa;"/>
</node>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287480833305" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1377258993" MODIFIED="1287480833305" TEXT="Module namespace initialization">
<node CREATED="1287480921499" ID="ID_293120670" MODIFIED="1291490176524" TEXT="In the package import model, the directory paths in your script become real &apos;&apos;nested object paths&apos;&apos; after an import."/>
<node CREATED="1287481014954" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1679286213" MODIFIED="1287503135894" TEXT="For instance, in the preceding example, after the import the expression `dir1.dir2` works and returns a module object whose namespace contains all the names assigned by `dir2`&#x2019;s `__init__.py` file. Such files provide a namespace for module objects created for directories, which have no real associated module files.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1287503268911" ID="ID_1151296797" MODIFIED="1287543377152" TEXT="/tmp/dir0$ python&#xa;Python 2.6.4 (r264:75706, Dec  7 2009, 18:43:55) &#xa;[GCC 4.4.1] on linux2&#xa;Type &quot;help&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;, &quot;credits&quot; or &quot;license&quot; for more information.&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1 &lt;-- &#x4e00;&#x6a23;&#x88ab;&#x8996;&#x70ba; module, &#x4f46; dir1.py &#x4e26;&#x4e0d;&#x5b58;&#x5728;&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1&apos; from &apos;dir1/__init__.py&apos;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; &#xa;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287483399571" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_837668878" MODIFIED="1287484074173" TEXT="&#x4e8b;&#x5be6;&#x4e0a; package &#x672c;&#x8eab;&#x4e5f;&#x53ef;&#x4ee5;&#x5b9a;&#x7fa9;&#x4e00;&#x4e9b;&#x8207; module files &#x540c;&#x540d;&#x7684; names, &#x5728;&#x67d0;&#x4e9b;&#x60c5;&#x6cc1;&#x4e0b;&#x6703;&#x6709; hide &#x7684;&#x6548;&#x679c;. (&#x5118;&#x53ef;&#x80fd;&#x8b93; package &#x55ae;&#x7d14;&#x7576;&#x70ba; container, &#x6216;&#x64d4;&#x8ca0; package initialization &#x7684;&#x8cac;&#x4efb;&#x5c31;&#x597d;)">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1287483452613" ID="ID_503722591" MODIFIED="1287483454352" TEXT="dir0">
<node CREATED="1287483464899" ID="ID_34915555" MODIFIED="1287483469758" TEXT="dir1">
<node CREATED="1287483471578" ID="ID_1767429356" MODIFIED="1287483475076" TEXT="__init__.py">
<node CREATED="1287483482272" ID="ID_1819846948" MODIFIED="1287483490849" TEXT="mod = &apos;string&apos;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287483475592" ID="ID_1767516503" MODIFIED="1287483477509" TEXT="mod.py"/>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287483509923" ID="ID_1394185401" MODIFIED="1287543388787" TEXT="/tmp/dir0$ python&#xa;Python 2.6.4 (r264:75706, Dec  7 2009, 18:43:55) &#xa;[GCC 4.4.1] on linux2&#xa;Type &quot;help&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;, &quot;credits&quot; or &quot;license&quot; for more information.&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1.mod&#xa;&apos;string&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; from dir1 import mod&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; mod&#xa;&apos;string&apos;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1.mod as real_mod&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; real_mod&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1.mod&apos; from &apos;dir1/mod.py&apos;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1.mod &lt;-- &#x540c;&#x6a23;&#x662f; dir1.mod, &#x7adf;&#x6703;&#x6709;&#x4e0d;&#x540c;&#x7684;&#x7d50;&#x679c;!!&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1.mod&apos; from &apos;dir1/mod.py&apos;&gt;&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; dir1.mod &lt;-- &#x986f;&#x7136; module &#x5f37;&#x904e; package &#x5e95;&#x4e0b;&#x7684; names&#xa;&lt;module &apos;dir1.mod&apos; from &apos;dir1/mod.py&apos;&gt;&#xa;&#xa;"/>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287484238316" ID="ID_280893681" MODIFIED="1287555349206" TEXT="`from *` statement behavior">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1287484256868" ID="ID_1300397035" MODIFIED="1287484336921" TEXT="As an advanced feature, you can use `__all__` lists in `__init__.py` files to define what is exported when a directory is imported with the `from *` statement form."/>
<node CREATED="1287484337134" ID="ID_638690559" MODIFIED="1291490464332" TEXT="In an `__init__.py` file, the `__all__` list is taken to be the &apos;&apos;list of submodule names&apos;&apos; (&#x8ddf; module file &#x7684;&#x7528;&#x6cd5;&#x4e0d;&#x540c;; list of string) that should be imported when `from *` is used on the package (directory) name."/>
<node CREATED="1287484367733" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1909539238" MODIFIED="1291490490164" TEXT="If `__all__` is not set, the `from *` statement does NOT automatically load submodules nested in the directory; instead, it loads just names defined by assignments in the directory&#x2019;s `__init__.py` file, including any submodules explicitly imported by code in this file.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1287484388178" ID="ID_1741387137" MODIFIED="1287484409060" TEXT="For instance, the statement `from submodule import X` in a directory&#x2019;s `__init__.py` makes the name `X` available in that directory&#x2019;s namespace."/>
<node CREATED="1287555524843" ID="ID_1729202110" MODIFIED="1287555654934" TEXT="&#x5176;&#x5be6;&#x5ba3;&#x544a; `__all__` &#x7684;&#x505a;&#x6cd5;&#x662f;&#x76f8;&#x5c0d;&#x6bd4;&#x8f03;&#x597d;&#x7684;, &#x96d6;&#x7136;&#x5df2;&#x7d93;&#x5c0f;&#x5fc3;&#x5955;&#x5955;&#x5730;&#x5c07;&#x975e;&#x516c;&#x958b;&#x7684; names &#x524d;&#x9762;&#x52a0;&#x4e0a; &apos;_&apos;, &#x4f46;&#x96e3;&#x514d;&#x6703; import &#x4e00;&#x4e9b; modules, &#x5982;&#x679c;&#x6c92;&#x6709;&#x523b;&#x610f;&#x5c07;&#x6a21;&#x7d44;&#x66f4;&#x540d; (&#x4f8b;&#x5982; `import sys as _sys`), &#x9084;&#x662f;&#x6703;&#x88ab; from * &#x62c9;&#x51fa;&#x53bb;...">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
</node>
</node>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287481398953" ID="ID_901357289" MODIFIED="1287481412867" TEXT="Don&#x2019;t confuse package `__init__.py` files with the class `__init__` constructor methods. The former are files of code run when imports first step through a package directory, while the latter are called when an instance is created. Both have initialization roles, but they are otherwise very different."/>
<node CREATED="1287548665005" ID="ID_248909352" MODIFIED="1287549029037" TEXT="&#x9019;&#x6a23;&#x7684;&#x898f;&#x5283; (&#x5f9e; leftmost &#x53bb;&#x627e; _`_init__.py`), &#x5f62;&#x6210;&#x4e86;&#x53e6;&#x4e00;&#x500b;&#x9650;&#x5236; - &#x6574;&#x4e32; package path &#x90fd;&#x5fc5;&#x9808;&#x5728;&#x540c;&#x4e00;&#x500b; parent folder &#x4e0b; (&#x9664;&#x975e;&#x6709; symbolic link, &#x4f46;&#x4e26;&#x975e;&#x4eba;&#x4eba;&#x90fd;&#x7528; Linux &#x958b;&#x767c;), &#x6c92;&#x6709;&#x8fa6;&#x6cd5;&#x50cf; Java classpath &#x7684;&#x591a;&#x500b;&#x8d77;&#x9ede;&#x6703;&#x5408;&#x4f75; (merge) &#x8d77;&#x4f86;.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<icon BUILTIN="messagebox_warning"/>
<node CREATED="1292481983434" ID="ID_194993027" LINK="http://efreedom.com/Question/1-3072644/Split-Python-Source-Separate-Directories" MODIFIED="1292482005915" TEXT="Split Python source into separate directories? - efreedom">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1292481975798" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_559107636" MODIFIED="1292481978027" TEXT="Example">
<node CREATED="1287548685667" ID="ID_1966369401" MODIFIED="1287548687101" TEXT="/tmp/dir0$ mkdir dir1; touch dir1/__init__.py&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ mkdir -p ext/dir1/dir2&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ touch ext/dir1/dir2/__init__.py&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ tree&#xa;.&#xa;|-- dir1&#xa;|   |-- __init__.py&#xa;|   `-- __init__.pyc&#xa;`-- ext&#xa;    `-- dir1&#xa;        `-- dir2&#xa;            `-- __init__.py&#xa;&#xa;4 directories, 3 files&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ export PYTHONPATH=/tmp/dir0/ext&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ python&#xa;Python 2.6.4 (r264:75706, Dec  7 2009, 18:43:55) &#xa;[GCC 4.4.1] on linux2&#xa;Type &quot;help&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;, &quot;credits&quot; or &quot;license&quot; for more information.&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1.dir2&#xa;Traceback (most recent call last):&#xa;  File &quot;&lt;stdin&gt;&quot;, line 1, in &lt;module&gt;&#xa;ImportError: No module named dir2&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; &#xa;/tmp/dir0$ touch ext/dir1/__init__.py&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ tree&#xa;.&#xa;|-- dir1&#xa;|   |-- __init__.py&#xa;|   `-- __init__.pyc&#xa;`-- ext&#xa;    `-- dir1&#xa;        |-- __init__.py&#xa;        `-- dir2&#xa;            `-- __init__.py&#xa;&#xa;4 directories, 4 files&#xa;/tmp/dir0$ python&#xa;Python 2.6.4 (r264:75706, Dec  7 2009, 18:43:55) &#xa;[GCC 4.4.1] on linux2&#xa;Type &quot;help&quot;, &quot;copyright&quot;, &quot;credits&quot; or &quot;license&quot; for more information.&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; import dir1.dir2&#xa;Traceback (most recent call last):&#xa;  File &quot;&lt;stdin&gt;&quot;, line 1, in &lt;module&gt;&#xa;ImportError: No module named dir2&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; &#xa;"/>
</node>
</node>
</node>
</node>
<node CREATED="1287545862032" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1099952788" MODIFIED="1287545865360" TEXT="Relative Imports">
<node CREATED="1287546095559" ID="ID_1338842579" MODIFIED="1287546284917" TEXT="Within the package itself, imports of package files can use the same path syntax as outside imports, but they can also make use of special &apos;&apos;intrapackage search rules&apos;&apos; to simplify `import` statements. That is, rather than listing package import paths, imports within the package can be relative to the package. (&#x53ea;&#x662f;&#x5beb;&#x6cd5;&#x4e0d;&#x540c;&#x800c;&#x5df2;, &#x4e26;&#x4e0d;&#x6703;&#x56e0;&#x6b64;&#x5f97;&#x5230;&#x4e0d;&#x540c; full name &#x7684;&#x591a;&#x500b; module instances)"/>
<node CREATED="1287546210127" ID="ID_1473297196" MODIFIED="1287546218269" TEXT="The way this works is &apos;&apos;version-dependent&apos;&apos; today: Python 2.6 &apos;&apos;implicitly&apos;&apos; searches package directories first on imports, while 3.0 requires &apos;&apos;explicit relative import syntax&apos;&apos;. This 3.0 change can &apos;&apos;enhance code readability&apos;&apos;, by making same-package imports more obvious.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
</node>
</node>
