<node CREATED="1300343851632" ID="ID_188108817" MODIFIED="1300343865586" TEXT="Class Properties">
<node CREATED="1300344629816" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_56931247" MODIFIED="1301039238122" TEXT="A mechanism known as properties provides another way for new-style classes&#xff08;&#x6709;&#x660e;&#x78ba;&#x7e7c;&#x627f; `object` &#x800c;&#x8a00;&#xff09; to define &apos;&apos;automatically called methods for access or assignment to instance attributes&apos;&apos;.">
<node CREATED="1300344642892" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1939646718" MODIFIED="1300344655825" TEXT="At least for specific attributes, this feature is an alternative to many current uses of the `__getattr__` and `__setattr__` overloading methods.">
<node CREATED="1300349692940" ID="ID_1485253754" MODIFIED="1300349694991" TEXT="&gt;&gt;&gt; class classic:&#xa;...     def __getattr__(self, name):&#xa;...         if name == &apos;age&apos;:&#xa;...             return 40&#xa;...         else:&#xa;...             raise AttributeError&#xa;...&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; x = classic()&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; x.age # Runs __getattr__&#xa;40&#xa;&gt;&gt;&gt; x.name # Runs __getattr__&#xa;AttributeError&#xa;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1300344656070" ID="ID_1070819785" MODIFIED="1300349369451" TEXT="Properties have a similar effect to these two methods, but they incur an extra method call for any accesses to names that require &apos;&apos;dynamic computation&apos;&apos;.&#xff08;`__getattr__` &#x8207; `__setattr__` &#x4e5f;&#x53ef;&#x4ee5;&#x81ea;&#x8a02;&#x904b;&#x7b97;&#xff0c;&#x53ea;&#x662f;&#x4e0d;&#x540c; names &#x7684;&#x908f;&#x8f2f;&#x6703;&#x6df7;&#x5728;&#x4e00;&#x8d77;&#x800c;&#x5df2;&#xff09;"/>
</node>
<node CREATED="1300354392199" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_339399983" MODIFIED="1300354585107" TEXT="Because such generic handlers can also handle simpler cases, properties are often an &apos;&apos;optional extension&apos;&apos;.">
<font BOLD="true" NAME="Monospaced" SIZE="12"/>
<node CREATED="1300354375894" ID="ID_1951906642" MODIFIED="1300354721928" TEXT="In such cases, a generic `__getattr__` or a `__setattr__` attribute handler with a passed-in attribute name may be preferable. "/>
<node CREATED="1300354353976" ID="ID_91673731" MODIFIED="1300354375516" TEXT="For example, in many cases, the set of attributes to be supported cannot be determined when the class is coded, and may not even exist in any tangible form (e.g., when delegating arbitrary method references to a wrapped/ embedded object generically)."/>
</node>
</node>
</node>
